<EFX_AUDITORS_OPINION>
<A NAME="FIS_AUDITORS_OPINION"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Re
</FONT>
<A NAME="MNRO-20160326X10K_HTM_REPORTOFINDEPENDENTREGISTREDPUBLICACCOUN">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	port of Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	To the Board of Directors and Shareholders of Monro Muffler Brake, Inc.:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In our opinion, the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	consolidated financial statements listed
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	accompanying index
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	present fairly, in all material respects, the financial position of Monro Muffler Brake, Inc. and its subsidiar
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ies
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	at March 2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and March 2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, and the results of their operations and their cash flows for each of the three years in the period ended March 2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America.&nbsp;&nbsp;Also in our opinion, the Company maintained, in all material respects, effective internal control over financial reporting as of March 2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, based on criteria established in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Internal Control - Integrated Framework
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	2013
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO).&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company's management is responsible for these financial statements, for maintaining effective internal control over financial reporting and for its assessment of the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting, included in Management's Report on Internal Control over Financial Reporting appearing under Item 9A.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our responsibility is to express opinions on these financial statements and on the Company's internal control over financial reporting based on our integrated audits.&nbsp;&nbsp;We conducted our audits in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States).&nbsp;&nbsp;Those standards require that we plan and perform the audits to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement and whether effective internal control over financial reporting was maintained in all material respects.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our audits of the financial statements included examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements, assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates made by management, and evaluating the overall financial statement presentation.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our audit of internal control over financial reporting included obtaining an understanding of internal control over financial reporting, assessing the risk that a material weakness exists, and testing and evaluating the design and operating effectiveness of internal control based on the assessed risk.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our audits also included performing such other procedures as we considered necessary in the circumstances.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our opinions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	A company&#x2019;s internal control over financial reporting is a process designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles.&nbsp;&nbsp;A company&#x2019;s internal control over financial reporting includes those policies and procedures that (i)&nbsp;pertain to the maintenance of records that, in reasonable detail, accurately and fairly reflect the transactions and dispositions of the assets of the company; (ii)&nbsp;provide reasonable assurance that transactions are recorded as necessary to permit preparation of financial statements in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles, and that receipts and expenditures of the company are being made only in accordance with authorizations of management and directors of the company; and (iii)&nbsp;provide reasonable assurance regarding prevention or timely detection of unauthorized acquisition, use, or disposition of the company&#x2019;s assets that could have a material effect on the financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

	Includes the receipt of treasury stock in connection with the exercise of stock options and to partially satisfy tax withholding obligations.

	&#x201C;we&#x201D;, &#x201C;us&#x201D;, or &#x201C;our&#x201D;), are engaged principally in providing automotive undercar repair and tire services in the United States.&nbsp;&nbsp;Monro had
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	1,029
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Company-operated stores,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	135
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	franchised location
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	14
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	dealer-operated automotive repair centers located in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	25
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	states as of March
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

</FONT>

	one
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	operating segment.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The accompanying Consolidated Financial Statements have been prepared in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles.&nbsp;&nbsp;The preparation of financial statements in conformity with such principles requires the use of estimates by management during the reporting period.&nbsp;&nbsp;Actual results could differ from those estimates.

<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="WIDTH:09.64%;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-LEFT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT SOLID #000000 ;BORDER-RIGHT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BACKGROUND-COLOR: #CCEEFF;HEIGHT:12.75PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;" NOWRAP="NOWRAP">
	27&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="WIDTH:01.88%;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-LEFT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT SOLID #000000 ;BORDER-RIGHT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BACKGROUND-COLOR: #CCEEFF;HEIGHT:12.75PT;PADDING:0PT;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;OVERFLOW: HIDDEN;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="WIDTH:01.60%;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-LEFT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-RIGHT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BACKGROUND-COLOR: #CCEEFF;HEIGHT:12.75PT;PADDING:0PT;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;OVERFLOW: HIDDEN;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="WIDTH:09.64%;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-LEFT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT SOLID #000000 ;BORDER-RIGHT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BACKGROUND-COLOR: #CCEEFF;HEIGHT:12.75PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;" NOWRAP="NOWRAP">
	28&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="WIDTH:01.88%;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-LEFT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT SOLID #000000 ;BORDER-RIGHT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BACKGROUND-COLOR: #CCEEFF;HEIGHT:12.75PT;PADDING:0PT;">

	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="WIDTH:01.60%;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-LEFT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-RIGHT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BACKGROUND-COLOR: #CCEEFF;HEIGHT:12.75PT;PADDING:0PT;">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Revenue from the sale of tire road hazard warranty agreements is recognized on a straight-line basis over the contract period or other method when costs are not incurred ratably.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Cash equivalents
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We consider all highly liquid instruments with original maturities of three months or less to be cash equivalents.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Inventories
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Our inventories consist of automotive parts and tires.&nbsp;&nbsp;Inventories are valued at the lower of cost or
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	net realizable
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	value using the first-in, first-out (FIFO) method.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	32
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
</HR>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage33"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#MNRO-20160326X10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 14PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:14PT;">
	MONRO MUFFLER BRAKE, INC. AND SUBSIDIARIES
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:1.5PT SOLID #000000 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	&#x2014; (Continued)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Barter credits
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We value barter credits at the fair market value of the inventory exchanged, as determined by reference to price lists for buying groups and jobber pricing.&nbsp;&nbsp;We use these credits primarily to pay vendors for purchases (mainly inventory vendors for the purchase of parts and tires) or to purchase other goods or services from the barter company such as advertising and travel.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Property, plant and equipment
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Property, plant and equipment are stated at cost.&nbsp;&nbsp;Depreciation of property, plant and equipment is provided on a straight-line basis.&nbsp;&nbsp;Buildings and improvements related to owned locations are depreciated over lives varying from
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	10
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	39
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	years; machinery, fixtures and equipment over lives varying from
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	15
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	years; and vehicles over lives varying from
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	10
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	years.&nbsp;&nbsp;Computer hardware and software is depreciated over lives varying from
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	years.&nbsp;&nbsp;Buildings and improvements related to leased locations are depreciated over the shorter of the asset&#x2019;s useful life or the reasonably assured lease term, as defined in the accounting guidance on leases.&nbsp;&nbsp;When property is sold or retired, the cost and accumulated depreciation are eliminated from the accounts and a gain or loss is recorded in the Consolidated Statements of Comprehensive Income.&nbsp;&nbsp;Expenditures for maintenance and repairs are expensed as incurred.&nbsp;&nbsp;(See Note&nbsp;4.)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Long-lived assets
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We evaluate the ability to recover long-lived assets whenever events or circumstances indicate that the carrying value of the asset may not be recoverable.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the event assets are impaired, losses are recognized to the extent the carrying value exceeds the fair value.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, we report assets to be disposed of at the lower of the carrying amount or the fair market value
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	less costs to sell
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Store opening and closing costs
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	New store opening costs are charged to expense in the fiscal year when incurred.&nbsp;&nbsp;When we close a store, the estimated unrecoverable costs, including the remaining lease obligation net of sublease income, if any, are charged to expense.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Leases
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Financing Obligations &#x2013;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We are often involved in the construction of leased stores.&nbsp;&nbsp;In some cases, we are respons
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ible for construction cost over
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	runs or non-standard tenant improvements.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result of this involvement, we are deemed the &#x201C;owner&#x201D; for accounting purposes during the construction period, requiring us to capitalize the construction costs on our Consolidated Balance Sheet.&nbsp;&nbsp;Upon completion of the project, we perform a sale-leaseback analysis pursuant to guidance on accounting for leases to determine if we can remove the assets from our Consolidated Balance Sheet.&nbsp;&nbsp;For some of these leases, we are considered to have &#x201C;continuing involvement&#x201D;, which precludes us from derecognizing the assets from our Consolidated Balance Sheet when construction is complete (&#x201C;failed sale-leaseback&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;In conjunction with these leases, we capitalize the construction costs on our Consolidated Balance Sheet and also record financing obligations representing payments owed to the landlord.&nbsp;&nbsp;We do not report rent expense for the properties which are owned for accounting purposes.&nbsp;&nbsp;Rather, rental payments under the lease are recognized as a reduction of the financing obligation and as interest expense.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Additionally, since we often assume leases in acquisition transactions, the accounting for a seller who was involved in the construction of leased stores passes to us.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Capital Leases &#x2013;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Some of our property is held under capital leases.&nbsp;&nbsp;These assets are included in property, plant and equipment and depreciated over the term of the lease.&nbsp;&nbsp;We do not report rent expense for capital leases.&nbsp;&nbsp;Rather, rental payments under the lease are recognized as a reduction of the capital lease obligation and interest expense.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Operating Leases &#x2013;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	All other leases are considered operating leases.&nbsp;&nbsp;Rent expense, including rent escalations, is recognized on a straight-line basis over the reasonably assured lease term, as defined in the accounting guidance on leases.&nbsp;&nbsp;Generally, the lease term is the base lease term plus certain renewal option periods for which renewal is reasonably assured.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	33
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>

	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage34"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#MNRO-20160326X10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 14PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:14PT;">
	MONRO MUFFLER BRAKE, INC. AND SUBSIDIARIES
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:1.5PT SOLID #000000 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	&#x2014; (Continued)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Goodwill and intangible assets
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We have a history of growth through acquisitions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Assets and liabilities of acquired businesses are recorded at their estimated fair values as of the date of acquisition.&nbsp;&nbsp;Goodwill represents costs in excess of fair values assigned to the underlying net assets of acquired businesses.&nbsp;&nbsp;The carrying value of goodwill is subject to annual impairment reviews in accordance with accounting guidance on goodwill, which we typically perform in the third quarter of the fiscal year.&nbsp;&nbsp;Impairment reviews may also be triggered by any significant events or changes in circumstances affecting our business.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We have
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	one
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	reporting unit which encompasses all operations including new acquisi
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	tions.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The goodwill impairment test consists of a t
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	wo-step process, if necessary.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We perform a qualitative assessment to determine if it is more likely than not that the fair value is less than t
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	he carrying value of goodwill.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The qualitative assessment includes a review of business changes, economic outlook, financial trends and forecasts, growth rates, industry data, market capitalization and other relevant qualitative factors. If the qualitative factors are triggered, we
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	perform the two-step process.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The first step is to compare the fair value of our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	reporting unit
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to the book
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	value of our reporting unit
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	If the fair value is less than its carrying value, the second step of the impairment test must be performed in order to determine the amount of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	impairment loss, if any.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The second step compares the implied fair value of goodwill with the carrying amount of that goodwill.&nbsp;&nbsp;If the carrying amount of goodwill exceeds its implied fair value, an impairment charge is recognized in an amount equal to that excess.&nbsp;&nbsp;The loss recognized cannot exceed th
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	e carrying amount of goodwill.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Intangible assets primarily represent allocations of purchase price to identifiable intangible assets of acquired businesses and are amortized over their estimated useful lives.&nbsp;&nbsp;All intangibles and other long-lived assets are reviewed when events or changes in circumstances indicate that the asset&#x2019;s carrying value may not be recoverable.&nbsp;&nbsp;If such indicators are present, it is determined whether the sum of the estimated undiscounted future cash flows attributable to such assets is less than their carrying amounts.&nbsp;&nbsp;No such indicators were present in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	fiscal
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	or 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	A deterioration of macroeconomic conditions may not only negatively impact the estimated operating cash flows used in our cash flow models, but may also negatively impact other assumptions used in our analyses, including, but not limited to, the estimated cost of capital and/or discount rates.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally, as discussed above, in accordance with accounting guidance, we are required to ensure that assumptions used to determine fair value in our analyses are consistent with the assumptions a hypothetical market participant would use.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result, the cost of capital and/or discount rates used in our analyses may increase or decrease based on market conditions and trends, regardless of whether our actual cost of capital has changed.&nbsp;&nbsp;Therefore, we may recognize an impairment of an intangible asset or assets even though realized actual cash flows are approximately equal to or greater than its previously forecasted amounts.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	As a result of our annual qualitative assessment performed in the third quarter of fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, there were
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	no
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	impairments.&nbsp;&nbsp;There have been no triggering events during the fourth quarter of fiscal 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Self-insurance reserves
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We are largely self-insured with respect to workers&#x2019; compensation, general liability and employee medical claims.&nbsp;&nbsp;In order to reduce our risk and better manage our overall loss exposure, we purchase stop-loss insurance that covers individual claims in excess of the deductible amounts
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, and caps total losses in a fiscal year
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;We maintain an accrual for the estimated cost to settle open claims as well as an estimate of the cost of claims that have been incurred but not reported.&nbsp;&nbsp;These estimates take into consideration the historical average claim volume, the average cost for settled claims, current trends in claim costs, changes in our business and workforce, and general economic factors.&nbsp;&nbsp;These accruals are reviewed on a quarterly basis, or more frequently if factors dictate a more frequent review is warranted.&nbsp;&nbsp;For more complex reserve calculations, such as workers&#x2019; compensation, we use the services of an actuary on an annual basis to assist in determining the required reserve for open claims.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Warranty
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We provide an accrual for estimated future warranty costs for parts that we install based upon the historical relationship of warranty costs to sales.&nbsp;&nbsp;Warranty expense related to all product warranties at and for the years ended March 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	was not material to our financial position or results of operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;See additional discussion of tire road hazard warranty agreements under the &#x201C;Revenue recognition&#x201D; section of this footnote.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Comprehensive income
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	As it relates to Monro, comprehensive income is defined as net earnings as adjusted for pension liability adjustments and is reported net of related taxes in the Consolidated Statements of Comprehensive Income and in the Consolidated Statements of Changes in Shareholders&#x2019; Equity.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	34

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 14PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:14PT;">
	MONRO MUFFLER BRAKE, INC. AND SUBSIDIARIES
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:1.5PT SOLID #000000 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">

</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Income taxes
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Deferred tax assets and liabilities are determined based on differences between the financial reporting and tax bases of assets and liabilities and are measured using tax rates based on currently enacted rules and legislation and anticipated rates that will be in effect when the differences are expected to reverse. The accounting guidance for uncertainties in income tax prescribes a comprehensive model for the financial statement recognition, measurement, presentation, and disclosure of uncertain tax positions taken or expected to be taken in income tax returns.&nbsp;&nbsp;Monro recognizes a tax benefit from an uncertain tax position in the financial statements only when it is more likely than not that the position will be sustained upon examination, including resolution of any related appeals or litigation processes, based on the technical merits and a consideration of the relevant taxing authority's administrative practices and precedents.&nbsp;&nbsp;(See Note 7.)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Treasury stock
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Treasury stock is accounted for using the par value method.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	During the year ended March 26, 2016, Monro&#x2019;s Chief Executive Officer surrendered
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	32,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shares of Monro&#x2019;s Common Stock at fair market value to pay the exercise price
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and the related taxes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	on the exercise of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	89,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	stock options.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally, Monro&#x2019;s Executive Chairman surrendered
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	100,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shares of Common Stock at fair market value to pay the exercise price and to satisfy tax withholding obligations on the exercise of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	150,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	stock options.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	During the year ended March 28, 2015, Monro&#x2019;s Chief Executive Officer surrendered
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	77,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shares of Monro&#x2019;s Common Stock at fair market value to pay the exercise price on the exercise of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	113,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	stock options.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;There was no activity for the Chief Executive Officer or Executive Chairman during the year ended March 29, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Stock-based compensation
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We measure compensation cost arising from the grant of share-based payments to an employee at fair value, and recognize such cost in income over the period during which the employee is required to provide service in exchange for the award, usually the vesting period.&nbsp;&nbsp;Forfeitures are estimated on the grant date and revised in subsequent periods if actual forfeitures differ from those estimates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We recognize compensation expense related to stock options using the straight-line approach.&nbsp;&nbsp;Option awards generally vest equally over the service period established in the award, typically
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	four
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	years.&nbsp;&nbsp;We estimate fair value using the Black-Scholes valuation model.&nbsp;&nbsp;Assumptions used to estimate the compensation expense are determined as follows:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">

</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="WIDTH: 14.00PT; DISPLAY: INLINE;">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;MARGIN:0PT;">

	&#xB7;

</TD>

</P>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;MARGIN:0PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Expected life of an award is based on historical experience and on the terms and conditions of the stock awards granted to employees;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;MARGIN:0PT;">

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;MARGIN:0PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Expected volatility is measured using historical changes in the market price of Monro&#x2019;s Common Stock;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>

<TD STYLE="WIDTH:36PT;">

</P>
</TD>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;MARGIN:0PT;">

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;MARGIN:0PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Risk-free interest rate is equivalent to the implied yield on zero-coupon U.S. Treasury bonds with a remaining maturity equal to the expected term of the awards;
</FONT>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH:100%;" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:36PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:36PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="WIDTH: 14.00PT; DISPLAY: INLINE;">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;MARGIN:0PT;">

</TD>

</P>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;MARGIN:0PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Forfeitures are based substantially on the history of cancellations of similar awards granted by Monro in prior years; and
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Earnings per share
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Basic earnings per share is calculated by dividing net income less preferred stock dividends by the weighted average number of shares of Common Stock outstanding during the year.&nbsp;&nbsp;Diluted earnings per share is calculated by dividing net income by the weighted average number of shares of Common Stock and equivalents outstanding during the year.&nbsp;&nbsp;Common Stock equivalents represent shares issuable upon the assumed exercise of stock options.&nbsp;&nbsp;(See Note 10.)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Advertising
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We expense the production costs of advertising the first time the advertising takes place, except for direct response advertising which is capitalized and amortized over its expected period of future benefits.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Direct response advertising consists primarily of coupons for Monro&#x2019;s services.&nbsp;&nbsp;The capitalized costs of this advertising are amortized over the period of the coupon&#x2019;s validity, which is typically
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	months.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Prepaid advertising at March 2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and March 2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, and advertising expense for the years ended March 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	4,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	were not material to these financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Vendor rebates and cooperative advertising credits
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We account for vendor rebates and cooperative advertising credits as a reduction of the cost of products purchased, except where the rebate or credit is a reimbursement of costs incurred to sell the vendor&#x2019;s product, in which case it is offset against the costs incurred.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Guarantees
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	At the time we issue a guarantee, we recognize an initial liability for the fair value, or market value, of the obligation we assume under that guarantee.&nbsp;&nbsp;Monro has guaranteed certain lease payments, primarily related to franchisees, amounting to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$10.4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million.&nbsp;&nbsp;This amount represents the maximum potential amount of future payments under the guarantees as of March 26, 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;The leases are guaranteed through April 2020.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the event of default by the franchise owner, Monro generally retains the right to assume the lease of the related store, enabling Monro to re-franchise the location or to operate that location as a Company-operated store.&nbsp;&nbsp;As of March 26, 2016, and in conjunction with purchase accounting, we have recorded a liability of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$.7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million related to anticipated defaults under the foregoing leases.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Recent accounting pronouncements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In May 2014, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#x201C;FASB&#x201D;) issued new accounting guidance for the reporting of revenue from contracts with customers.&nbsp;&nbsp;This guidance provides guidelines a company will apply to determine the measurement of revenue and timing of when it is recognized.&nbsp; In March 2016, the FASB finalized its amendments to this guidance on assessing whether an entity is a principal or an agent in a revenue transaction.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The amendment provides clarification on principal versus agent considerations by providing indicators that suggest control.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The guidance impacts whether an entity records revenue on a gross versus net basis.&nbsp;&nbsp;In August 2015, the FASB delayed the effective date of the guidance to fiscal years and interim periods within those years beginning after December 15, 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;Early adoption is permitted, but not before the original effective date for public entities.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are currently evaluating the potential effect of the adoption of this guidance on our Consolidated Financial Statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In April 2015, the FASB issued new accounting guidance related to the presentation of debt issuance costs.&nbsp;&nbsp;This guidance
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	requires
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability to be presented on the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the debt liability rather than as an asset.&nbsp;&nbsp;These costs will continue to be amortized to interest expense using the effective interest method.&nbsp;&nbsp;This pronouncement is effective for fiscal years and for interim periods within those years beginning after December 15, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Retrospective adoption is required.&nbsp;&nbsp;In September 2015, the FASB issued guidance clarifying that debt issuance costs related to revolver and line of credit arrangements can be recorded as an asset and amortized over the term of the arrangement, which is consistent with Monro&#x2019;s current presentation.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	This guidance did not
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	have a material effect on our Consolidated Financial Statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	36
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>

	&nbsp;

<A NAME="eolPage37"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#MNRO-20160326X10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 14PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:14PT;">
	MONRO MUFFLER BRAKE, INC. AND SUBSIDIARIES
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:1.5PT SOLID #000000 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	&#x2014; (Continued)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In April 2015, the FASB issued new accounting guidance related to the measurement date of an employer's defined benefit obligation and plan assets.&nbsp;&nbsp;This guidance permits a reporting entity with a fiscal year-end that does not coincide with a month-end to measure defined benefit plan assets and obligations using the month-end that is closest to the entity's fiscal year-end and apply that practical expedient consistently from year to year. The
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	guidance
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	is effective for financial statements issued for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2016 and interim periods within those fiscal years.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The new guidance is consistent with Monro&#x2019;s current presentation.&nbsp;&nbsp;This guidance
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	did not have a material impact on our Consolidated Financial Statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In July 2015, the FASB issued new accounting guidance for the reporting of inventory.&nbsp;&nbsp;This guidance requires that inventory within the scope of the guidance be measured at the lower of cost and net realizable value.&nbsp;&nbsp;This guidance is effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2016, with ea
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	rly adoption permitted.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have elected early
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	adoption of this guidance
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	during the fourth quarter of fiscal 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;The adoption of this guidance did not have a material impact
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	on our Consolidated Financial Statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In September 2015, the FASB issued new accounting guidance that is intended to simplify the accounting for adjustments made to provisional amounts recognized in a business combination by eliminating the requirement to retrospectively account for those adjustments.&nbsp;&nbsp;This guidance requires an entity to present separately on the face of the income statement or disclose in the notes the amount recorded in current period earnings by line item that would have been recorded in previous reporting periods if the adjustment to the provisional amounts had been recognized as of the acquisition date.&nbsp;&nbsp;This guidance is effective for fiscal years and for interim periods within those years beginning after December 15, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have adopted this guidance during the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	fourth quarter of fiscal
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;Adoption of this guidance did not have a material effect on our Consolidated Financial Statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In November 2015, the FASB issued new accounting guidance related to the balance sheet classification of deferred taxes.&nbsp;&nbsp;This guidance will require that deferred tax assets and liabilities be classified as noncurrent in a classified balance sheet.&nbsp;&nbsp;This guidance is effective for fiscal years and interim periods within those years beginning after December 15, 2016, with early adoption permitted.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have elected early adoption of this guidance during
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	fourth quarter
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of fiscal
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016, utilizing retrospective application as permitted.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result, we have presented all net deferred tax assets and liabilities as noncurrent on our consolidated balance sheet as of March 26, 2016 and March 28, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;For the classified balance sheet as of March 28, 2015, we have reclassified current deferred tax assets of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$13,942,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	as noncurrent deferred tax assets.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In February 2016, the FASB issued new accounting guidance related to leases.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This guidance establishes a right of use (ROU) model that requires a lessee to record a ROU asset and lease liability on the balance sheet for all leases with terms longer than twelve months.&nbsp;&nbsp;Leases will be classified as either finance or operating, with classification affecting the pattern of expense recognition.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The standard is effective for financial statements issued for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2018 and interim periods within those fiscal years.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A modified retrospective transition approach is required for lessees for capital and operating leases existing at, or entered into after, the beginning of the earliest comparative period presented in the financial statements, with certain practical expedients available.&nbsp;&nbsp;Early adoption is permitted.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We are currently evaluating the effect of the adoption of this
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	guidance
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	on our Consolidated Financial Statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In March 2016, the FASB issued new accounting guidance intended to simplify various aspects related to accounting for share-based payments and their presentation in the financial statements. This guidance is effective for fiscal years and interim periods within those years beginning after December 15, 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Early adoption is permitted.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are currently evaluating the potential impact of the adoption of this guidance on our Consolidated Financial Statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Other recent authoritative guidance issued by the FASB (including technical corrections to the Accounting Standards Codification) and the Securities and Exchange Commission did not, or are not expected to have a material effect on our Consolidated Financial Statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTE 2 &#x2013; ACQUISITIONS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Monro
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2019;s acquisitions are strategic moves in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	plan to fill in and expand
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	presence in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	existing and contiguous markets, and leverage fixed operating costs such as distribution and advertising.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

	29

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;MARGIN:0PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	On April 25, 2015, we acquired the Car-X Brand, as well as the franchise rights for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	146
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	auto service centers from Car-X Associates Corp., a subsidiary of Tuffy Associates Corp.&nbsp; At the time of acquisition, the Car-X stores were owned and operated by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	32
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	independent Car-X franchisees in Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kentucky, Minnesota, Missouri, Ohio,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Tennessee
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	, Texas and Wisconsin.&nbsp;&nbsp;The franchise locations operate under the Car-X name.&nbsp;&nbsp;Monro operates as the franchisor through a standard royalty agreement, while Car-X remains a separate and independent brand and business through Car-X, LLC, Monro&#x2019;s wholly-owned subsidiary, with franchise operations based in Illinois.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	The
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	se
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	acquisitions resulted in goodwill related to, among other things, growth opportunities, synergies and economies of scale expected from combining these businesses with ours, and unidentifiable intangible assets. All of the goodwill is expected to be deductible for tax purposes. We have recorded finite-lived intangible assets at their estimated fair value related to customer relationships, trade name
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	, franchise agreements
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	and favorable leases.
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;

</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	$
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	.7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	million for the year ended March 26, 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;These costs are included in the Consolidated Statements of Comprehensive Income primarily under operating, selling, general and administrative expenses.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

	Sales

	, including franchise royalty income,
</FONT>

	and net income for the fiscal 2016 acquired entities totaled
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">

</FONT>

	24.8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	million and approximately
</FONT>

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">

</FONT>

	five
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	-year,
</FONT>

</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:1.5PT SOLID #000000 ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In December 2012, the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Revolving
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Credit Facility was amended to include the following: the committed sum was increased by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$75
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$250
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million; the term was extended for another
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	one
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and a half years, such that the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Revolving
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Credit Facility
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	was to expire
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	December 2017
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	; and the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$75
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million accordion feature was maintained. There were no other changes in terms including those related to co
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	venants or interest rates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	On January 25, 2016, we entered into a new
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	five
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	-year
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$600
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million Revolving Credit Facility agreement with
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	nine
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	banks (the &#x201C;Credit Facility&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;Interest only is payable monthly throughout the Credit Facility&#x2019;s term.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Credit Facility increases our current borrowing capacity from our prior financing agreement by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$350
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million to $600 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and includes an accordion feature permitting us to request an increase in availability of up to an additional
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$100
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million, an increase of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$25
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million from our prior financing agreement.&nbsp;&nbsp;The expanded facility bears interest at
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	75
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	175
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	basis points over LIBOR.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Credit Facility requires fees payable quarterly throughout the term between
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.15%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.35
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of the amount of the average net availability under the Credit Facility during the preceding quarter.&nbsp;&nbsp;There was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$103.3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million outstanding under the Credit Facility at March 26, 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;We were in compliance with all debt covenants as of March 26, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Specific terms of the Credit Facility permit the payment of cash dividends not to exceed
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	50%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of the prior year&#x2019;s net income, and permit mortgages and specific lease financing arrangements with other parties with certain limitations.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Other specific terms and the maintenance of specified ratios are generally consistent with our prior financing agreement.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Additionally, the Credit Facility is not secured by our real property, although we have agreed not to encumber our real property, with c
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ertain permissible exceptions.
</FONT>
</P>

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="WIDTH:01.26%;BORDER-TOP:1PT SOLID #000000 ;BORDER-LEFT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:2PT DOUBLE #000000 ;BORDER-RIGHT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;HEIGHT:12.75PT;PADDING:0PT;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="WIDTH:22.16%;BORDER-TOP:1PT SOLID #000000 ;BORDER-LEFT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:2PT DOUBLE #000000 ;BORDER-RIGHT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;HEIGHT:12.75PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;" NOWRAP="NOWRAP">
	6,929&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The total amount of unrecognized tax benefits was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$6.9
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million at March 2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, the majority of which, if recognized, would affect the effective tax rate.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In the normal course of business, Monro provides for uncertain tax positions and the related interest and penalties, and adjusts its unrecognized tax benefits and accrued interest and penalties accordingly.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	During the year ended March 28, 2015, we recognized interest and penalties of approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$.1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million, in income tax expense; and during the year ended March 29, 2014, we recorded a benefit from the reversal of accrued interest and penalties of approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$.1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million in income tax expense.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;Additionally, we had approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million of interest and penalties associated with uncertain tax benefits accrued as of March 2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and March 2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	60%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of the Class C preferred stock must approve any action authorized by the holders of Common Stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, there are certain restrictions on the transferability of shares of Class C preferred stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the event of a liquidation, dissolution or winding-up of Monro, the holders of the Class C preferred stock would be entitled to receive
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$1.50
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	per share out of the assets of Monro before any amount would be paid to holders of Common Stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;The conversion value of the Class C convertible preferred stock was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$.064
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	per share at March 2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and March 2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTE 9 &#x2013; SHARE BASED COMPENSATION
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Monro currently grants stock option awards under the 2007 Incentive Stock Option Plan (the &#x201C;2007 Plan&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;The 2007 Plan was authorized by the Board of Directors in June 2007, initially reserving
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	873,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shares (as retroactively adjusted for stock splits) of Common Stock for issuance to eligible employees and all non-employee directors.&nbsp;&nbsp;The 2007 Plan was approved by shareholders in August 2007.&nbsp;&nbsp;Prior to fiscal 2008, Monro had options outstanding under
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	three other stock option plans:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the 1994 Non-Employee Directors Stock Option Plan (the &#x201C;1994 Plan&#x201D;) (which was approved by shareholders in August 1995); the 1998 Incentive Stock Option Plan (the &#x201C;1998 Plan&#x201D;) (which was approved by shareholders in August 1999); and the 2003 Non-Employee Directors Stock Option Plan (the &#x201C;2003 Plan&#x201D;) (which was approved by shareholders in August 2003), collectively the &#x201C;Prior Plans&#x201D;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;Upon shareholder approval of the 2007 Plan, all shares of Common Stock available for award under the 1998 and 2003 Plans were transferred to, and made available for award under the 2007 Plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;The 1994 Plan had no options available for grant upon adoption of the 2007 Plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;No further option grants may be made under the Prior Plans, although outstanding awards under the Prior Plans will remain outstanding in accordance with the terms of those plans and the stock option agreements entered into under those plans.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The 1994 Plan had a total of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	675,345
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	common shares authorized for issuance; the 1998 Plan had a total of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	4,016,250
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shares authorized for issuance; and the 2003 Plan had a total of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	315,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shares authorized for issuance (all as retroactively adjusted for stock splits).&nbsp;&nbsp;Upon authorization of the 2007 Plan by shareholders,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	628,620
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shares (as retroactively adjusted for stock splits) were transferred from the 1998 and 2003 Plans into the 2007 Plan, bringing the total authorized shares to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	1,501,620
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	(as retroactively adjusted for stock splits).&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, in May 2013 and 2010, the Compensation Committee of the Board of Directors authorized an additional
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2,000,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	1,500,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shares (as retroactively adjusted for stock splits), respectively, of common stock for grant under the 2007 Plan, which were approved by shareholders in August 2013 and August 2010, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;At March 2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, there was a total of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5,001,62
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shares authorized for grant under the 2007 Plan (as retroactively adjusted for stock splits), including the shares transferred from the 1998 and 2003 Plans.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

	Generally, employee options vest
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	over a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	year period
</FONT>

	, and have a duration of
</FONT>

	six
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	years.&nbsp;&nbsp;Outstanding options are exercisable for various periods through March 202

	4
